<rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom" xmlns:media="http://search.yahoo.com/mrss/" xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/"><channel><title>NYT &gt; Technology</title><link>https://www.nytimes.com/section/technology</link><description>Technology industry news, commentary, and analysis, with reporting on big tech, startups, and internet culture. The New York Times is a hub for conversation about news and ideas.</description><atom:link rel="self" href="https://rss.nytimes.com/services/xml/rss/nyt/Technology.xml" type="application/rss+xml" /><item><title>Meta Begins Laying Off 8,000 Employees Amid A.I. Transformation</title><link>https://www.nytimes.com/2026/05/19/technology/meta-layoffs-ai.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</link><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.nytimes.com/2026/05/19/technology/meta-layoffs-ai.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</guid><atom:link rel="standout" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2026/05/19/technology/meta-layoffs-ai.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss" /><description>Meta told employees last month that it would carry out mass layoffs on May 20, as the Silicon Valley giant tries to transform into an A.I.-first company.</description><dc:creator>Eli Tan and Kalley Huang</dc:creator><pubDate>Tue, 19 May 2026 20:00:05 GMT</pubDate><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Social Media</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Artificial intelligence</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Jobs</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Layoffs</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Furloughs</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Computers and the Internet</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Tech Industry</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Workplace</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Facebook</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Instagram</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Meta</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">WhatsApp</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Andrew Bosworth</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Mark E Zuckerberg</category><media:content url="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2026/05/19/multimedia/9biz-meta-layoffs-hpkt/9biz-meta-layoffs-hpkt-videoSixteenByNineJumbo1600.jpg" medium="image"><media:credit>Ian C. Bates for The New York Times</media:credit><media:description>Meta’s headquarters in Menlo Park, Calif. The company, which renamed itself for the metaverse, is transforming itself for the era of artificial intelligence.</media:description></media:content></item><item><title>Senate Republicans Introduce Funding Measure to Combat Online Child Abuse</title><link>https://www.nytimes.com/2026/05/19/technology/senate-republicans-funding-combat-online-child-abuse.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</link><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.nytimes.com/2026/05/19/technology/senate-republicans-funding-combat-online-child-abuse.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</guid><atom:link rel="standout" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2026/05/19/technology/senate-republicans-funding-combat-online-child-abuse.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss" /><description>As part of the reconciliation bill, the senators have allocated $108 million over three years to add nearly 200 specialists at the Department of Homeland Security.</description><dc:creator>Cecilia Kang</dc:creator><pubDate>Tue, 19 May 2026 14:57:44 GMT</pubDate><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">US Politics</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Child Abuse</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Legislation</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Children</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Computers and the Internet</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Tech Industry</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Josh Hawley</category><media:content url="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2026/05/19/multimedia/19biz-CONGRESS-CSAM-cqlk/19biz-CONGRESS-CSAM-cqlk-videoSixteenByNineJumbo1600.jpg" medium="image"><media:credit>Kenny Holston/The New York Times</media:credit><media:description>Senator Josh Hawley, Republican of Missouri, has championed the reconciliation bill.</media:description></media:content></item><item><title>Five Takeaways From the Blockbuster Trial Pitting Elon Musk Against OpenAI</title><link>https://www.nytimes.com/2026/05/18/technology/elon-musk-openai-trial-takeaways.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</link><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.nytimes.com/2026/05/18/technology/elon-musk-openai-trial-takeaways.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</guid><atom:link rel="standout" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2026/05/18/technology/elon-musk-openai-trial-takeaways.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss" /><description>It took a jury less than two hours to decide that Mr. Musk had waited too long to sue. But the testimony over three weeks was still illuminating.</description><dc:creator>Cade Metz</dc:creator><pubDate>Mon, 18 May 2026 21:07:32 GMT</pubDate><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Artificial intelligence</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Lawsuits</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Decisions and Verdicts</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Nonprofit</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">OpenAI</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Elon Musk</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Sam Altman</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Greg Brockman</category><media:content url="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2026/05/18/multimedia/18biz-openai-trial-takeaways-1-gqtc/18biz-openai-trial-takeaways-1-gqtc-videoSixteenByNineJumbo1600.jpg" medium="image"><media:credit>Jason Henry for The New York Times</media:credit><media:description>The federal courthouse in Oakland, Calif., on Monday, when a jury decided that Elon Musk had waited too long to file his lawsuit against OpenAI.</media:description></media:content></item><item><title>Rising Energy Costs and Data Centers at Heart of NextEra’s Dominion Bid</title><link>https://www.nytimes.com/2026/05/19/business/energy-environment/nextera-dominion-electricity-rates-data-centers.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</link><guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.nytimes.com/2026/05/19/business/energy-environment/nextera-dominion-electricity-rates-data-centers.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss</guid><atom:link rel="standout" href="https://www.nytimes.com/2026/05/19/business/energy-environment/nextera-dominion-electricity-rates-data-centers.html?partner=rss&amp;emc=rss" /><description>NextEra’s proposed acquisition of Dominion Energy comes as Americans are paying a lot more for electricity, and data centers are demanding a lot more power from utilities.</description><dc:creator>Ivan Penn</dc:creator><pubDate>Tue, 19 May 2026 15:13:37 GMT</pubDate><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Mergers and Acquisitions</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">Electric power</category><category domain="http://www.nytimes.com/namespaces/keywords/nyt_des">